{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the working directory. For each file, return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count; 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp); 3) up to 20 unique cmdb_id values; 4) up to 20 unique KPI/trace/log name values (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv; for error_logs.csv, list unique message samples up to 20); 5) the top 5 rows (showing only timestamp, cmdb_id, and the metric/trace/log name column and value/message column). Limit all lists to at most the requested counts."}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded the four telemetry files and produced a compact summary. metric.csv is large (147,732 rows) covering the full incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 to ~07:59:00 CST; trace.csv and log.csv also span the same interval; error_logs.csv contains 309 rows and shows repeated warning messages from frontend pods (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2) beginning around 07:30:05. From this we can already suspect frontend pods as candidates, but we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds on metrics first (using the full series), then extract incident-window data and detect anomalies. The next step should identify which component-KPI time series show the most pronounced anomalies in the incident window so we can narrow candidates for trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, do the following and keep results in kernel variables for later steps: 1) For every unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and global P5 using the full available metric series (no time filtering). Store as metric_thresholds (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, count_points). 2) Filter metric.csv to only rows with timestamp >= 1647819000 and < 1647820800 (the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 to 08:00:00 CST). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the incident window compute: number of points with value >= global_p95 (anomaly_count_p95_high), number of points with value <= global_p5 (anomaly_count_p5_low), total_anomalies (sum of the two), earliest_anomaly_epoch (the earliest timestamp among those anomaly points), earliest_anomaly_local (local time string), max_value_incident, min_value_incident. Use the global thresholds computed in step 1 when deciding anomalies. Store the incident-window metric rows as metric_incident and the aggregated anomaly summary as metric_anomaly_summary. 4) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) showing the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by total_anomalies desc, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_p95_high, anomaly_count_p5_low, total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_epoch, earliest_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, global_p95, global_p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs scanned. Keep the output bounded and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric-level anomaly scan was completed. Global thresholds (P95/P5) were computed for 4,934 distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs across the full metric series. After filtering to the incident window (2022-03-21 07:30:00–08:00:00 CST) metric_incident contains 147,732 rows. The top-20 anomaly summary is dominated by shippingservice2-0 with many KPIs whose kpi_name contains 'container.node-5.*' (e.g., container_memory_max_usage_MB, container_fs_writes, container_network_receive_err, etc.). These entries report 60 total anomalies each (30 >= global P95 and 30 <= global P5) with earliest anomaly at the very start of the window (1647819000 -> 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST). This strongly suggests something related to node-5 (the node hosting shippingservice2-0) is abnormal at the start of the incident window. Error logs previously showed repeated warnings from frontend pods starting ~07:30:05, so there may be correlated symptoms across layers. However, metric anomalies alone do not yet confirm whether the root cause is container-level (shippingservice2-0), node-level (node-5), or a cascading downstream service. According to the prescribed workflow, we should next perform trace-level anomaly aggregation (global thresholds on trace features across the full trace series, then incident-window filtering) to find which service/container traces show latency or error-rate degradations and to identify the most downstream faulty component in call chains.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On trace.csv: 1) For every unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and global P5 using the full available trace series (no time filtering). Save as trace_thresholds (cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p5, count_points). 2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window timestamp >= 1647819000 and < 1647820800 and save as trace_incident. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the incident window compute: anomaly_count_p95_high (points with value >= global_p95), anomaly_count_p5_low (points with value <= global_p5), total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_epoch (earliest timestamp among anomaly points), earliest_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident. Store summary as trace_anomaly_summary. 4) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) sorted by total_anomalies desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count_p95_high, anomaly_count_p5_low, total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_epoch, earliest_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, global_p95, global_p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,trace_name) pairs scanned. Keep outputs bounded (no full time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-level analysis was completed. Global P95/P5 thresholds were computed for 1,240 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs using the full trace series, and incident-window trace rows (25,480) were scanned. The top anomalies are dominated by error_rate and some duration KPIs, but many of those series have global_p95 == global_p5 == 0.0, which causes points equal to 0.0 to be counted as both high and low anomalies (double-counting). Metric analysis earlier strongly pointed to shippingservice2-0 (many KPIs labeled container.node-5.*) with earliest anomalies at 1647819000 (2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST), suggesting a node-5 related issue starting at the window start. Error logs previously showed repeated warnings from frontend pods starting ~07:30:05. To localize the root cause and reason we must now inspect logs: (1) metric and trace point to node-5 / shippingservice2-0 as suspicious, (2) traces show many zero-threshold artifacts so we must rely on logs to determine whether the underlying reason is resource exhaustion, network, or process-level errors. Next step: run compact log-level anomaly aggregation and summarize error_logs counts and earliest occurrences to see which components logged warnings/errors and when.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) On log.csv: compute global P95 and global P5 for every (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full log series (no time filtering). Save as log_thresholds (cmdb_id, log_name, global_p95, global_p5, count_points). 2) Filter log.csv to incident window timestamp >= 1647819000 and < 1647820800 and save as log_incident. 3) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) within the incident window compute: anomaly_count_p95_high (value >= global_p95), anomaly_count_p5_low (value <= global_p5), total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_epoch, earliest_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident. Store summary as log_anomaly_summary. 4) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of top 20 (cmdb_id, log_name) sorted by total_anomalies desc with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, anomaly_count_p95_high, anomaly_count_p5_low, total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_epoch, earliest_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, global_p95, global_p5. Also return total number of distinct (cmdb_id, log_name) pairs scanned and the number of incident-window log rows. \n\nAdditionally, 5) On error_logs.csv: aggregate counts per cmdb_id within the incident window, and for the top 5 cmdb_id by count return: cmdb_id, count, earliest_error_epoch, earliest_error_local, up to 5 distinct sample messages for that cmdb_id. Return only this compact top-5 summary (no full raw records). Keep all outputs bounded (top tables only)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected node-5 related KPIs and found their reported anomalies are artifacts: all incident-window points equal the global P95 and P5 (count_points_incident=30, count_values_eq_global_p95=30, count_values_eq_global_p5=30, count_values_not_equal_thresholds=0). Thus shippingservice2-0 / node-5 entries are not showing real deviations in the incident window — they only triggered because our anomaly logic counted equality to thresholds twice. Metrics, traces, and logs earlier pointed at many components with large aggregated anomaly counts, but those totals are polluted by this equality double-counting. Error logs show frontend pods produced many warning messages beginning a few seconds after the window start (~07:30:05), indicating symptomatic failures at the frontend layer.\n\nWhat must be done next: Re-evaluate metric anomalies using strict comparisons to remove equality artifacts and surface KPIs with genuine deviations. That will narrow true faulty components for subsequent trace/log correlation. Specifically, use the previously computed global thresholds (metric_thresholds) and the incident window rows (metric_incident), but count an anomaly only when value > global_p95 (strict high) or value < global_p5 (strict low). Aggregate these strict-anomaly counts per (cmdb_id, kpi_name), compute earliest strict-anomaly timestamp, and return the top 20 series by strict total_anomalies. This will let us identify components with real metric departures to prioritize trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric_thresholds and metric_incident already stored in the kernel, re-evaluate anomalies with strict comparisons: \n1) For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in metric_incident, compute: count_points_incident, anomaly_count_high_strict = count of rows with value > corresponding global_p95, anomaly_count_low_strict = count with value < corresponding global_p5, total_anomalies_strict = sum of the two, earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch (earliest timestamp among rows satisfying either condition), earliest_strict_anomaly_local (local time string), max_value_incident, min_value_incident. Use metric_thresholds to join global_p95/global_p5. \n2) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by total_anomalies_strict desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_high_strict, anomaly_count_low_strict, total_anomalies_strict, earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch, earliest_strict_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, global_p95, global_p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs scanned. Keep outputs bounded (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We re-evaluated metric anomalies using strict rules (value > global_p95 or value < global_p5). This removed equality artifacts (many 'node-5' KPIs were only equal to thresholds and are therefore not real deviations). With strict rules the true metric deviations are much fewer and concentrate on frontend-1 (many mesh/istio request/response metrics) and a small number of node/system KPIs (e.g., node-2 system.fs.inodes.total). Earliest strict anomalies for most frontend KPIs are at the start of the window (2022-03-21 07:30:00 UTC+8). Separately, error_logs show many frontend warnings starting seconds later (frontend-0 earliest 07:30:05, frontend-1/2 similar). Taken together: metrics point to frontend-layer issues (frontend-1 most prominent by strict metric deviation) and some node/system anomalies elsewhere; node-5 artifacts were false positives. We still need trace-level strict-anomaly analysis to determine which service or container is the most downstream FAULTY component in call chains (trace data will help pick the last faulty service/container). Until we examine strict trace anomalies and correlate with traces/logs, we cannot confidently state the single root cause component, exact occurrence time, or reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace_thresholds and trace_incident already stored in the kernel, re-evaluate anomalies with strict comparisons: for each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) in trace_incident compute anomaly_count_high_strict = count(value > global_p95), anomaly_count_low_strict = count(value < global_p5), total_anomalies_strict (sum), earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch (earliest timestamp among strict anomalies), earliest_strict_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident. Join to trace_thresholds to obtain global_p95 and global_p5. Return a compact top-20 table sorted by total_anomalies_strict desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count_high_strict, anomaly_count_low_strict, total_anomalies_strict, earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch, earliest_strict_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, global_p95, global_p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,trace_name) pairs scanned. Keep outputs bounded (no full raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We completed strict (>P95 / <P5) re-evaluation for metrics and traces. Summary of what has been done: global thresholds were computed using full series; incident-window rows were filtered; anomaly logic was changed to strict comparisons to remove equality artifacts. Results show that many previously-flagged anomalies (notably the 'node-5' KPIs for shippingservice2-0) were artifacts caused by values equal to both P95 and P5; those are not real deviations. After switching to strict rules, genuine metric deviations are much fewer and concentrate on frontend-layer KPIs (frontend-1 especially, many mesh/istio metrics) and a small number of node/system KPIs (e.g., node-2 fs/inodes). Trace strict anomalies are sparse and distributed across several services (recommendationservice2-0, adservice2-0, productcatalogservice-1, frontend2-0, checkoutservice2-0) with earliest strict deviations at various times in the window (07:30 through 07:47+). Error logs show many frontend warning messages beginning seconds after window start (frontend-0 earliest 07:30:05). What can be derived so far: the most consistent signal across metrics, traces, and logs points to problems at the frontend layer (frontends show strict metric deviations and many error/warning messages shortly after 07:30:00). However, we have not yet proven whether the frontend is the root cause (it could be symptomatic) nor determined the underlying resource reason (CPU/memory/network/process). To localize the root cause component and exact occurrence time, we must focus on frontend pod-level KPIs and their logs to see which frontend pod first shows a strict metric fault and what error messages indicate (e.g., timeouts, connection errors, OOMs, process crashes). Therefore the next step is to produce a focused, bounded summary of strict metric anomalies for frontend pods to identify the earliest strict fault among them and the most implicated KPI(s).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric_incident and metric_thresholds stored in the kernel, focus on frontend components only: filter metric_incident to cmdb_id in ['frontend-0','frontend-1','frontend-2','frontend2-0','frontend'] (match exact strings). For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count_points_incident, anomaly_count_high_strict (value > global_p95), anomaly_count_low_strict (value < global_p5), total_anomalies_strict (sum), earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch (earliest timestamp among rows meeting strict conditions), earliest_strict_anomaly_local, max_value_incident, min_value_incident, and up to 5 distinct sample_values from the incident window. Use metric_thresholds to obtain global_p95 and global_p5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name). Return two bounded tables only: 1) top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) rows sorted by total_anomalies_strict desc with the columns above plus global_p95 and global_p5; 2) an aggregated per-cmdb_id summary for these frontend cmdb_ids showing cmdb_id, sum_total_anomalies_strict (sum of total_anomalies_strict), num_kpis_with_strict_anomaly, earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch, earliest_strict_anomaly_local. Keep outputs limited to these two tables (max 20 rows each)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous attempt to get a detailed per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) table for frontend components failed to complete. From prior results we know: (1) equality-to-threshold artifacts were removed by switching to strict >P95 / <P5 rules; (2) strict metric anomalies concentrate in frontend-1 (mesh/istio KPIs) with earliest strict anomalies at the start of the window (~2022-03-21 07:30:00 UTC+8); (3) error_logs show many frontend warnings a few seconds after the window start (frontend-0 earliest 07:30:05). To make progress while keeping the Executor's work smaller and more robust, we should first obtain a compact per-frontend summary (rather than many per-KPI rows) that identifies which frontend pod first exhibited any strict metric anomaly and which KPI types contributed most. This will narrow the candidates for trace/log inspection and help localize the root cause component/time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric_incident and metric_thresholds already in the kernel, produce a compact frontend-focused summary: 1) Restrict to cmdb_id in ['frontend-0','frontend-1','frontend-2','frontend2-0','frontend'] present in metric_incident. 2) For each such cmdb_id compute: distinct_kpis_with_strict_anomaly (count of kpi_name where any incident-row has value > global_p95 or value < global_p5), total_strict_anomaly_points (sum of rows across all KPIs that satisfy strict conditions), earliest_strict_anomaly_epoch (min timestamp among those strict-anomaly rows), earliest_strict_anomaly_local (local time string), and total_incident_rows_for_cmdb. 3) Additionally, for each cmdb_id return up to the top 5 kpi_name values (kpi_name and strict_anomaly_point_count) sorted by strict_anomaly_point_count desc to show which KPIs contribute most. 4) Return two bounded tables only: (A) per-cmdb_id summary (one row per frontend cmdb_id), (B) per-cmdb_id top-kpis (rows limited to 5 per cmdb_id). Keep outputs limited to these aggregates (max 20 rows total) and do not print raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps computed global thresholds and ran anomaly detection (first with >=/<= which produced equality artifacts, then re-run with strict >/< rules). Metric strict anomalies concentrated at the frontend layer (frontend-0/1/2/frontend2-0) with earliest strict metric anomalies at 1647819000 (2022-03-21 07:30:00 UTC+8). Error logs show frontend warnings beginning at 1647819005 (frontend-0). Trace strict anomalies are sparse and some have earliest strict anomalies at 1647819000 as well. Node-5 (shippingservice2-0) KPI anomalies were shown to be artifacts (values equal to thresholds) and therefore not real deviations. At this stage we have strong symptomatic signals at the frontend layer: earliest metric deviations at 07:30:00 and error messages from frontend pods starting at 07:30:05. To confidently localize the root cause we need to identify the absolute earliest strict anomaly across metrics and traces (component, KPI/trace name, timestamp, and severity) and compare that to earliest frontend error logs. This will tell us whether a frontend pod metric deviation occurred first (suggesting frontend as the root cause) or whether a downstream service/trace showed a fault earlier (suggesting upstream cause).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric_incident + metric_thresholds and trace_incident + trace_thresholds already in the kernel, find the absolute earliest strict anomaly in metrics and in traces within the incident window as follows (keep outputs bounded): \n1) Metrics: locate incident-window rows where value > global_p95 or value < global_p5. For those rows compute deviation_ratio = abs(value - (global_p95 if value>global_p95 else global_p5)) / (abs(global_p95) if value>global_p95 else (abs(global_p5)+1e-12)). Return up to 10 rows with the earliest timestamp(s) (sorted by timestamp asc) showing columns: timestamp, timestamp_local, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, global_p5, is_high_anomaly (True if value>global_p95 else False), deviation_ratio. If multiple rows share the same earliest timestamp, include them up to 10 rows. \n2) Traces: locate incident-window rows where value > global_p95 or value < global_p5. Compute the same deviation_ratio logic (use global_p95 for high, global_p5 for low). Return up to 10 earliest rows sorted by timestamp asc with columns: timestamp, timestamp_local, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, global_p95, global_p5, is_high_anomaly, deviation_ratio. \n3) Also return the overall earliest frontend error log timestamp and cmdb_id from the previously aggregated error_logs (you already computed these, but re-return the earliest frontend error: timestamp and timestamp_local and cmdb_id). \nKeep all outputs compact (max 10 rows per list) and do not print full raw time series. This will allow direct comparison of earliest metric/trace strict anomalies vs earliest frontend error log time."
}

